 scholars who engage allegory in exciting new ways. The contributors include Jody Enders, Karen Feldman, Angus Fletcher, Blair Hoxby, Brenda Machosky, Catherine Gimelli Martin, Stephen Orgel, Maureen Quilligan, James Paxson, Daniel Selcer, Gordon Teskey, and Richard Wittman. The essays are not limited to an examination of literary texts and works of art, and in fact focus on a wide range of topics that includes architecture, philosophy, theatre, science, and law. The book proves the truth of the statement that all language is allegorical, and more importantly it shows its consequences. To "think allegory otherwise" is to think otherwise- to rethink not only the idea of allegory itself, but also the law and its execution, the literality of figurative abstraction, and the figurations upon which even hard science depends.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAllegoryvCongresses. 0aAllegoryxCongressesxElectronic booksxConference proceedings. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aFletcher, Angus J. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoxby, Blair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMachosky, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Catherine Gimelli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSelcer, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTeskey, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaxson, James J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnders, Jody, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuilligan, Maureen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab